161 years ago today, Northwestern University held its inaugural classes in a three-story, wood-frame structure that came to be known as Old College. 

The building was uprooted from a plot at Davis and Hinman and relocated to the Fisk Hall area in 1871. It moved to its final location in 1899 where the McCormick-Tribune Center stands today. Alas, its wood frame was ill-fated, and Old College was razed in 1973 after a lightning strike and sprinkler malfunction. A plaque commemorates the structure's original downtown Evanston home on the Hinman Street side of the former Davis Street Fish Market. #NorthwesternDirection

#TheForceIsStrong but tiny: The world's smallest #MillenniumFalcon was created by Microscopy & Imaging Specialist, Eric Miller of NUANCE Center at Northwestern University.

Made from platinum on silicon substrate and built in an FEI Helios Focused Ion Beam microscope, the actual size is 19.5 micrometers long by 14 micrometers wide ‚Äì approximately 1:1,800,000 scale. Comparatively speaking, a red blood cell is a mere 8 micrometers across!

#TheForceAwakens, and alumnus Cooper Carter has been rocking YouTube for 10 days and over 500,000 hits with his mega tribute to #StarWars and its theme song composer, John Williams. http://bit.ly/1N7FCVS

Here's another post in our collaboration with People of NU to feature stories from seniors in the Northwestern Class of 2014. Meet Communication senior Darcy Coussens.

Q: " How does your theatre major help you to become a better human being?"
A: "As Prof. David Catlin put it, and I am paraphrasing here, 'To study or to do theatre is to investigate what it is to be a human being'. I think doing theatre means you can apply it to anything. It gives you a strong sense of compassion for other people. Every character that I played, I have tried to understand them, to think how they will think. It teaches you a lot about putting yourself in other people's shoes and that applies anywhere you go in life."

Q: " What are the challenges you faced here?"
A: "Managing my time and my mental balance. I think it is a common thing at Northwestern for students to take on a lot. My peers are so capable and we take on too much and we manage to do it all. That takes a lot of time. So I become good managing myself and also realizing I need to see good friends that are important to me, to eat a good meal and to go for a run by the lake. It is really easy to lose sight of these things when you are doing so much. That's important but the smaller things are important, too. By the end of senior year I am realizing that more and more."

Q: "How do you rate your social life here at NU?"
A: "I think it is very subjective but at Northwestern most students have been able to find a community that they feel they belong to. For me it is not just one community. I feel like I have different groups of people where I fit in. I worked at the Northwestern Phonathon and that is a very exciting and awesome group of people that are very outgoing and diverse. There is the student community here, which is overwhelmingly generous with their time. We just made a lot of theatre together and everyone goes to see each other in their productions. I was also really lucky to visit the NU campus on Doha. The students on the trip I went with were a nice community. They are mostly film, communication studies and journalism students. That's where I made lots of friends. It's been really great to find different niches that I feel I am not just in one place. I really like that."

Q: "Do you have any questions you want to ask other students on campus?"
A : " Hmm, OK, have you guys figured out what to do with your life? Cause I don't necessarily know. What I do know is what I like to study and what I like to do. I don't necessarily know how that is going to translate into a career. I have skills from everything I have done here at Northwestern. So I am just gonna find somewhere those skills are useful and look for ways to make art and to do the stuff I like to do. Hopefully I will be able to do all of that which will also pay the bills."

¬©2014 Sean Su

Here's another post in our collaboration with People of NU to feature stories from seniors in the Northwestern Class of 2014. Meet Weinberg senior Joanna Jaros.

Q: "Who is the best teacher you ever had during your time at NU?"
A: "My best teacher is Prof. Vinzenz Unger. He is absolutely brilliant, very blunt and down to earth! I just took one class with him and that's enough to make a lasting impact on me."

Q: " What do you want to do after graduation?"
A: "I am going to work as a project manager for an electronic medical record company and I am currently applying to medical school."

Q: " What advice do you want to give to the new students on campus?"
A: " Just embrace the experience and make the best of it. Don't get too stressed out and keep going!"

Q: "If you could go back to talk to your freshman year self, what would you want to say?"
A: "Relax and get involved early, then just roll with it!"

Photo ¬© 2014 Sean Su

Here's another post in our collaboration with People of NU to feature stories from seniors in the Northwestern Class of 2014. Meet senior twins Valentina Garces and Manuela Garces.

Q: "What are your majors?"

A: "Both of our majors are communication studies with minors in economics and we will both do a one year master program of management studies in Kellogg after graduation. We are following the same tracks."

Q: "Do you have any special powers as twins?"

A: "We can read each other's mind just by looking at each other. For example if she looked the other way I will know what she was trying to tell me. We have the same cues and primers. She can start a sentence, stop in the middle and I will be able to finish the rest."

Q: "What were the funniest experiences when growing up as twins?"

A: "When we were little we took each other's test and we switched classes. I was in a gifted class and she wanted to try it out because she was going to be there too. So I switched class with her. The principal only found out 6 months later. And she laughed and laughed and who sold us out were another pair of twins who were our best friends."

Q: "What was it like to have a twin sister on campus?"

A: "We were always together. We have been roommates since the junior year. We really like studying in the same place. It just helps when you have someone by your side to remind you what the professor said in the class."

Q: "Who helped you the most on campus?"

A: "It has to be Debra Webster our academic adviser from School of Communication. She is like a second mom to us. Whenever we feel stressed we will go to her and she will calm us down and help us out." 

Q: "What is the best advice she ever gave you?"

A: "The best advice she gave us is to follow our passion. She used to say, 'Do not do everything just because your classmates or friends do. Always challenge yourself but also take into account your passion.'"

Q: "What advice do you want to give to people who are not twins?"

A: "They might feel a little bit alienated when they are around us. Because we have this special connection, we can talk to each other just by looking at each other or showing little gestures and they do not know how to deal with it. But since being together all the time and having this special bond, as twins we are actually more open and receptive than normal people. So just talk to us and do not feel freaked out."

Photo ¬© 2014 Sean Su with Valentina Garces in green jacket and
Manuela Garces in light brown jacket.

Here's another post in our collaboration with People of NU to feature stories from seniors in the Northwestern Class of 2014. Meet School of Education and Social Policy senior Megan McEvily.

Q: "Who inspired you on campus?"
A: "I would like to say some of the professors, but I think some of the students that were older than me were really my role models."

Q: "Do you have any advice you would give to your younger self?"
A: "That's so difficult. I think when things get hard, it is easier when you're doing them with friends. For any kind of challenge, doing hard things with friends makes them easier."

Q: "What was you biggest challenge in your time here?"
A: "I was in a sorority and I was on the sailing team too. Splitting my time between those was really hard because I loved them both a lot. But I cared about them both so much that splitting my time was worth it. Even though I was really busy, it was okay because it was with things I was passionate about."

Q: "Anything else you want to add?"
A: "Do what makes you happy and keep doing it!"

Photo ¬© 2014 Sean Su

Here's another post in our collaboration with People of NU to feature stories from seniors in the Northwestern Class of 2014. Meet Weinberg senior Danny Ginzburg.

Q: "What is something you are proud of in you time here at NU?"

A: "My senior year, I was one of the co-chairs of Green Cup. It's something I'm passionate about which is environmental sustainability, both education and action. We were able to save the university thousands of dollars on energy reductions which I think is really cool. It was a fun opportunity for me to manage a large group of people with a shared vision."

Q: "Do you plan on taking anything you've learned from that into your future post-graduation life?"
A: "That's a great question. I'll be essentially doing professional Green Cup starting on Monday, working at a firm called Goby in city. They do energy and sustainability consulting for commercial real estate."

Q: "Do you have one piece of advice for new students?"

A: "For anyone who really wants to get the most out of their time both at Northwestern and in Life, from my limited experience, I would say sit yourself down and ask yourself the following questions:

1) What makes you unique?
2) What makes you happy?
3) What is a problem in the world that you want to work to solve?
4) Are you currently doing things in your life that make you happy and that solve those problems?

And I want you to write down those questions and your answers in a big bold marker and tape them above your desk so you can look at them every single day. And I promise you that if you look at those answers everyday and ask yourself am I doing these things? You'll find that you will be a happier and more disciplined person and you will be leading a much more meaningful life."

Photo ¬© 2014 Sean Su

Here's the third in our collaboration with People of NU to feature stories from seniors in the Northwestern Class of 2014. Meet Weinberg senior Zoe Palmer.

Q: "What is your proudest moment so far on campus?"

A: "My proudest moment as a student on campus was doing my senior reading! I wrote fiction as part of creative writing sequence.I am a senior with double majors in creative writing and cognitive science, and yes, I know that's a weird combination. Think of it as two different ways to study people. Likewise I wrote weird fiction published in Every Day Fiction, Prompt, and forthcoming in Swamp Biscuits and Tea."

Q: "How does the experience here at Northwestern help you to become a writer?"

A: "To become a writer you have to do it every day. Writing is not something you could dip in and out. The classes I took here keep me doing it all the time. The trick is to read a lot and keep at it to find your inspirations. You also learn rules of writing by reading a lot."

Q: "What are the basic rules you have to know to become a great writer?"

A: "Some of the basic rules are‚Äîto make it exciting‚Äîyour character has to have some stakes. They have to want something or something has to be interfering with what they want. Otherwise it is not a story, it is just a chronicle of events. At sentence level, vary your sentence length and structure and keep it away from getting boring. Another piece of advice I guess I would say is to pay attention to real life, pay attention really closely to the world around you. You never know if you might observe a very interesting detail that might make a great note in the story, or you see a really interesting person that will make a great character. Cause real life is full of little wired incongruities, and those make great elements of a story."

¬© 2014 Sean Su

Here's the second in our collaboration with People of NU to feature stories from seniors in the Northwestern Class of 2014. Meet Weinberg senior Mariam Gomaa.

Q: "What's one piece of advice you'd share with others?"

A: "Don't let other people, kind of, put you down or tell you that you can't do something because I think for me, I'm a Creative Writing and Bio double major, it's like really weird. And a lot of people told me at the beginning that, you know like, why would you do that? Or, like, you can't do that, that's so much. Or they don't make sense together...I just don't believe in that. I think that if you really want to do everything, you can. I'm a photographer and a writer, I volunteer... I do a lot of stuff and it's never taken away from my experience in any way. It's only made me feel like a more full human being."

¬© 2014 Sean Su

Leading up to graduation, we're partnering with People of NU to feature the unique stories and perspectives of members of the Northwestern Class of 2014.

Q: "What was your hardest decision at Northwestern?"

A: "Oh man, to change my major and not be able to graduate on time. I switched out of Bienen to McCormick when I was so close to finishing the degree. Like it would've almost been a formality to finish there, and a lot of people were pressuring me to do that. For me it was a great decision--well maybe not financially--but in general if you stay longer people kind of see that as a failure. Like it's pretty rare not to graduate on time and if you don't it's probably because of some extenuating circumstances. But I can't say that, I was just doing one thing and, like, a completely new idea bashed me over the head and I just ran with it." -Kyle

¬© 2014 Sean Su

When the Wildcats played Nebraska on October 3, 1931, Al Capone and a few of his gang members were in attendance. From their seats in the 45th row of Dyche stadium in Evanston, "Scarface" and his henchmen were jeered and booed throughout the game. Capone left at the end of the third quarter, but it was already evident that Northwestern had won their first home game of the season 19 ‚Äì 7. Check out this vintage reaction from The Daily Northwestern.

As his 74th birthday comes to a close, here are a few more photos of Willie the Wildcat through the years. He's had some epic reinventions and aged pretty gracefully...Do you remember any of these looks?

Happy 74th birthday to Willie Wildcat!

According to a Daily Northwestern article from 1942, Willie made his debut on a poster drawn by James McAndrew in 1937. Upon seeing the poster, a newspaper writer dubbed the wildcat "Willie," and the name stuck. Willie's debut as a live mascot occurred 10 years later. Although his physical appearance has changed over the years, he's still as popular as ever, and getting a photo with Willie remains a rite of passage for Northwestern students. Happy birthday, Willie!

status_message: Yesterday was a sad day for some of Northwestern's oldest residents, as a brief but violent storm uprooted some of the oldest trees on the Evanston campus. Thankfully no one was injured, but wind gusts blew over trees between Kresge Hall and University Library, as well as a few willow trees on the lakefill. On May 31, 1850, nine men met in a law office above a Chicago hardware store to plan the founding of a new university. 161 years later, Northwestern is better than ever. status_message: Chicago Tribune cartoonist Scott Stantis celebrates Professor Dale Mortensen's Nobel win in a way all Wildcats can appreciate...

Northwestern economist Dale Mortensen has won the 2010 Nobel Prize in Economics! He shares the prize Peter Diamond of MIT and Christopher Pissarides of the London School of Economics and Political Science. The trio's work centers around the ways in which unemployment, job vacancies and wages are affected by regulation and economic policy! Congratulations to Professor Mortensen!
link_name: Mortensen Wins Nobel Pirze : Northwestern University Newscenter

via Northwestern Athletics: The 'Cats get revenge against North Carolina. Final score: 15-10 NU!!. We'll take on  Maryland at 4:30 p.m. CT Sunday!! On the line? A six-peat! Go 'Cats!

via Northwestern Athletics: It's game day for Northwestern Lacrosse at the NCAA Final Four! Good luck to the 'Cats as they look to bring home a sixth consecutive national championship! link_name: Wildcats Draw Rematch With Tar Heels in National Semifinal - NORTHWESTERN OFFICIAL ATHLETIC SITE

status_message: Commencement is right around the corner... And Northwestern magazine has profiled some of our seniors that you'll want to keep an eye on as they head out into the "real world." Congratulations to the Class of 2010! Good luck on your final finals!

On to the Final Four!!! After defeating Duke 18-8, the lacrosse team is headed to suburban Baltimore for a national semifinal match-up against North Carolina next weekend! The Tar Heels are the only team to beat the Wildcats thus far this season! Good luck to head coach Kelly Amonte Hiller and her 'Cats as they seek revenge against UNC... and a six-peat as national champs!!!
link_name: Back To Towson!! Northwestern Routs Duke, 18-8, in NCAA Quarterfinal - NORTHWESTERN OFFICIAL ATHLETI

status_message: One of Northwestern's own is lending his expertise to the newest incarnation of a Hollywood science fiction franchise. McCormick professor and robotics expert Malcolm MacIver is a technical script consultant for the new show "Caprica," which premiers tomorrow on the SyFy channel. The show is a prequel to Battlestar Galactica. MacIver says the gig is another way for him to bring scientific concepts and ideas to the public. So, tune in... and watch out for those Cylons.
link_name: Malcolm MacIver Works as Script Consultant for New Show 'Caprica'
